all number of projects, the UK’s CfD mechanism offers </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">support beyond single demonstration plants and the opport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unity for the UK to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gain advantages from being an early mover.   </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The benefits of CCS range from the opportunity to build domestically and in international markets, a global leadership in the CCS industry, which if deployed extensively globally cold rival</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the oil and gas industry in the sale of investment involved.   The employment and trade benefits to the UK would be extensive.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The USA has used CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for Enhanced Oil Recovery for more than 30 years and today some 6% of US oil production is produced this w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ay.  The UK’s North Sea oil industry has a large </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">number of oil fields that are at a point in their life where the use of CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for EOR and storage could significantly increase the proportion of oil that can be recovered.   If widely used, this technology cou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ld deliver billions of pounds of incremental tax revenue to The Treasury and extend the life of oil fields with all the associated employment and security of energy supply benefits that flow from that.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Work by the AEA has estimated benefits for UK-based</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> firms to be £3-6.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5bn per annum in the late 2020s but the case for CCS would be better understood and appreciated if there was a comprehensive analysis of the economic, fiscal and social benefits of CCS.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the main barriers (e.g. economic, politi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">cal, regulatory, scientific and social) to developing large-scale integrated CCS projects in the UK and internationally?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> How can they be overcome? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The principal barrier to the development of large-scale integrated CCS projects is the lack of the policy i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ncentives with sufficient long term certainty that will make what are multi-billion projects bankable.  The UK is addressing this with the creation of Contracts for Difference under the Electricity Market reform process.  However, EMR does not provided any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> clarity on longer term CCS objectives.  The draft Delivery Plan released in July includes scenarios which show anything from virtually no CCS projects through to a possible 12GW by 2030 whereas </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">greater clarity exists for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">renewable technologies</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> lack</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of clarity</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> around support for CCS also extends to a lack</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of guidance on a CfD price setting and allocation process for CCS projects. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The technologies needed for the construction and operation of large scale CCS projects - carbon capture, CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> transporta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tion and storage – are all proven at scale in different industries around the world and do not require further development to be used in the first large scale CCS projects.  It is the integration of these technologies to create a new CCS industry that is n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ovel.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Are there any safety issues associated with capturing, transporting and storing carbon dioxide?  How could they be overcome?  Who should have responsibility for ensuring these activities are safe?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> capturing, transporting and storage of CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> are all activities that are already carried out safely at scale in different industries around the world. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EU </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CCS Directive, implemented by the UK, has already put in place the framework for the regulation of the industry.  The Directive may be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> possibly revised as early as</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2015. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">While there are concerns in the industry about </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">onerou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s and unpredictable liabilities </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> storage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in saline formations in the EU, 2Co does not anticipate the issue causing the same concerns where the CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is used </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for Enhanced Oil Recovery and storage.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><br /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:115%; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How have other countries incentivised CCS development?  How successful have they been?  How do they compare with the UK’s efforts?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The majority of CCS projects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that are making the most progress</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> share at least three of four aspects of what is an emerging business model for early stage CSS projects:-</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A capital grant to assist with project development and possibly as a contribution to capital expenditure (examples include the EU (EEPR and NER300 pr</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ogrammes), UK, Canada and USA).</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Enhanced Oil Recovery </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to reduce the overall costs of CCS by offering low, or zero, cost CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:sub">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> storage.  In some onshore situations, such as the USA, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rather than acting as a cost to the project it is a commodity with a value </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and can be sold.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government backed debt as an important source of funding and to reduce the costs of financing.  For instance, there have been Federal backed loans available in the USA and export credit agencies (such as Japanese and Chinese) are active.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A premium price for the cost of the low-carbon electricity that will support the operation of the plant.  The UK’s Contract for Difference</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is an example.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:15pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Is the UK government’s approach, set out in its CCS Roadmap, likely to incentivise development of C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">CS in the UK?</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As both the original plans for a CCS project at Peterhead and the UK government’s first CCS competition failed to lead to the construction of the UK’s first CCS large-scale CCS project, industry is wary.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The current government has also scale</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d back its ambition for support for four projects to a maximum of two.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The approach in the roadmap also seems to lack pace and scale.  </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The Commercialisation Programme and work on follow-on projects need to move in parallel.  If there is a hiatus after t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he commercialisation programme, the opportunities afforded by early mover advantage will be lost, companies will dis-band CCS teams and move activity overseas and it will take the UK years to re-establish the skills and experience that have been nurtured t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">o date.  In order to justify continued investment, the CCS industry needs a clear signal there will be a CCS market in the long term in the UK. </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If project partners and investors are to be comfortable about committing additional funds in projects that are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> not part of the Commercialisation Programme, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">they will quickly </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">need greater clarity around the process and timing of support under the CfD mechanism</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  These projects need the EMR process to establish a predictable CCS CfD strike price setting and allocati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on process that offers a bankable CfD for CCS.</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; line-height:15pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What are the consequences of failing to develop CCS and what alternatives are available for decarbonisation if CCS fails?</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">If widespread deployment of CCS in the UK does not start now the costs of meeting UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">emissions reduction targets w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ill be significantly higher than</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would otherwise be the case.  Delaying deployment of CCS until the 2020s or 2030s and trying to deploy CCS at a faster rate would stretch supply chains and drive up costs considerably.  </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Given t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he technologies used in CCS are all proven at scale around the world, 2Co does not foresee CCS failing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">technically.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  The company’s detailed estimates of costs also give 2Co confidence CCS is a cost competitive source of low-carbon power.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">principal ris</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">k to the success of CCS is a lack of pace and scale in CCS policy and whether the CfD for CCS will be fit for purpose.</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Fossil fuels </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">still account for the majority of power generated in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">UK and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are an important part of a robust and diverse electricity su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">pply for the country.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">CCS is the only way to secure the future of the UK’s coal mining and coal power industries and also the longer term future for the natural gas power generation industry while also meeting the UK’s legally binding emissions reduction </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">targets.  </span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">With CCS</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> fossil fuels can fill an important role in meeting</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e energy demands of a low-carbon future</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> – both as baseload power and as flexible power to balance the intermittency of renewables</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:15pt; margin:0pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>